The objective of this class is to become more familiar and comfortable with the academic writing genre in English. Although language mechanics (e.g. grammar) will, of course, play a role, the primary focus will be on the "formula" for writing an academic paper in English.

Choosing a topic/research question, finding sources, the organization of English academic writing, citing/referencing sources, formatting, and peer editing will all be addressed. The final outcome will be a single academic English research paper of approximately 6,000 words (10 pages).

The class style will alternate between lecture/discussion and student-led editing sessions.

Students are encouraged to participate actively and openly in class.

";
第1回 Overview
An introduction to the course and a look at an example research paper

第2回 Defining your Research Question / Finding Sources
We will discuss finding a general research question, and then finding sources to help you answer it. We will also discuss resource management software, with an emphasis on Zotero (free!).

第3回 The Reference Section & Citations / Formatting Your Document
This session will give an overview of the reference section of an academic paper. I will also demonstrate basic document formatting techniques for English academic writing.

第4回 Thesis Statements / Outline
Once you have settled on a topic for your paper, you need to narrow it down to exactly what you want to say about it.

第5回 The Introduction
We will view and discuss some effective introductions to academic papers.

第6回 Peer Editing 1: The Introduction
In this class we will learn about how to do peer editing and use the process to edit each others' introductions.

第7回 Organization of Claims and Support
In this session, we will discuss the issue of claims and support. We will discuss what statements need support, and what do not. We will also discuss how to organize information to be easy for the reader to process.

第8回 Citations, Quotations and Plagiarism
In this session, we will discuss the related topics of citing your sources in your writing, quoting sources, and when using too much of what a source has said is plagiarism. This is a very serious and important topic for any student who may be studying in and English-speaking country in the future!

第9回 Peer-Editing 2: Body, Round 1
We will peer-edit the main body of your research paper.

第10回 Peer-Editing 3: Body, Round 2
We will peer-edit the main body of your research paper again.

第11回 The Conclusion
In this session, we will discuss and view some effective ways to conclude an academic paper.

第12回 Peer Editing 4: Conclusion
We will peer-edit the conclusion of your paper.

第13回 Penultimate Peer Editing Session / Conferences
We will peer-edit the paper, and I will meet one-on-one with students to discuss the latest draft

第14回 Final Peer Editing Session
We will take this day to edit the papers one more time. Due date for the finished product will be announced in class.

